Average variable cost, AVC,

02:28:07.980 --> 02:28:09.820
is the variable cost

02:28:09.940 --> 02:28:11.780
per unit of production.

02:28:12.780 --> 02:28:13.940
How to count them?

02:28:14.480 --> 02:28:17.340
We divide the total amount of variable costs

02:28:17.340 --> 02:28:19.000
by the volume of production.

02:28:19.160 --> 02:28:20.880
Look at the formula.

02:28:21.580 --> 02:28:25.680
And finally, the average

02:28:25.680 --> 02:28:29.920
total cost is the total cost

02:28:30.000 --> 02:28:32.020
per unit of production.

02:28:33.940 --> 02:28:34.880
How to calculate?

02:28:35.820 --> 02:28:37.720
Total cost, TC, can

02:28:37.720 --> 02:28:40.220
be divided by

02:28:40.220 --> 02:28:40.960
Q.

02:28:42.020 --> 02:28:43.760
Or else can be counted.

02:28:44.240 --> 02:28:46.540
Average constant and variable

02:28:46.540 --> 02:28:49.840
costs can be summed up.

02:28:53.430 --> 02:28:56.950
A very important role in economic

02:28:56.950 --> 02:29:01.170
analysis is played by marginal

02:29:01.390 --> 02:29:02.450
cost.

02:29:03.570 --> 02:29:06.270
Limit costs are the increase

02:29:06.270 --> 02:29:09.570
in total costs when the output

02:29:09.570 --> 02:29:12.630
increases by one unit.

02:29:13.090 --> 02:29:15.110
Look at the formula.

02:29:15.290 --> 02:29:20.170
mc is equal to delta TC divided by

02:29:20.170 --> 02:29:21.390
delta Q.

02:29:21.710 --> 02:29:22.990
How to understand?

02:29:24.290 --> 02:29:26.650
Let's say, you have already

02:29:26.650 --> 02:29:29.290
produced a few units.

02:29:30.810 --> 02:29:35.290
You want to produce another

02:29:35.290 --> 02:29:38.170
additional product.

02:29:40.190 --> 02:29:43.190
Another additional product.

02:29:43.690 --> 02:29:46.710
To produce an additional unit

02:29:46.710 --> 02:29:49.710
of products, additional costs

02:29:49.710 --> 02:29:52.090
must be incurred.

02:29:52.410 --> 02:29:55.690
These additional costs, which

02:29:55.970 --> 02:29:57.950
will be required by the production

02:29:57.950 --> 02:30:00.390
of an additional unit of product,

02:30:00.950 --> 02:30:04.610
are the limit costs.

02:30:04.870 --> 02:30:06.970
But look when we increase

02:30:06.970 --> 02:30:08.130
the issue?

02:30:10.610 --> 02:30:13.210
When will the total cost increase?

02:30:13.210 --> 02:30:17.370
The total costs are consisting

02:30:17.370 --> 02:30:19.770
of fixed and variable costs.

02:30:20.310 --> 02:30:23.830
Only variable costs increase.

02:30:23.990 --> 02:30:26.450
Fixed costs are not changed over

02:30:26.450 --> 02:30:30.150
a short period of time.

02:30:31.870 --> 02:30:35.610
The increase in total costs is

02:30:35.610 --> 02:30:40.750
equal to the increase in variable costs.

02:30:41.170 --> 02:30:44.010
Thus, the limit costs can be calculated

02:30:44.010 --> 02:30:47.570
by dividing the delta of the growth

02:30:47.570 --> 02:30:49.690
of variable costs, divided by the

02:30:49.990 --> 02:30:52.110
